\details{
\subsection{Clipping}{

Candidate propensity scores are clipped to \code{clip} (default
[0.01, 0.99], the paper's constants) \strong{before} averaging. The average is
never re-clipped: a convex combination of values inside the clipping
interval cannot leave it.
}

\subsection{Criterion vs. display conventions}{

The \code{smd}/\code{prog} \emph{selection criteria} standardize all columns (including
binary ones) by the plain unweighted sample SD of the \code{s.d.denom} group --
the paper's convention (its reference \code{Fasmd} uses \code{sd()}), implemented by
passing \code{bin.vars = FALSE} for every column to \code{\link[cobalt:col_w_smd]{cobalt::col_w_smd()}}. The
display-oriented \code{balance} component and \code{\link[=bal.tab.psave]{bal.tab.psave()}} follow
\pkg{cobalt}'s native conventions (binary columns use
\eqn{\sqrt{p(1-p)}}). For \code{criterion = "prog"} the denominator is a
positive constant across the \eqn{\lambda} grid, so the selected
\eqn{\lambda} is invariant to this choice; the \emph{reported}
\code{criterion.value} uses the paper's convention. For the KS criterion the
two conventions coincide on binary columns.
}

\subsection{Relation to other software}{

The closest existing functionality is \link[WeightIt:method_super]{WeightIt::method_super} with
\code{SL.method = "method.balance"} (Pirracchio and Carone 2018): a
covariate-balance-targeted SuperLearner for \emph{weighting only}. \pkg{psAve}
differs in targeting \strong{prognostic-score} balance (Hansen 2008; Stuart,
Lee and Leacy 2013), in searching an exhaustive simplex grid with a
documented tie-break instead of a convex-optimization meta-learner, and in
returning a plain score vector equally usable for \strong{matching}
(\code{MatchIt::matchit(distance = )}) and weighting. No other package
implements propensity score model averaging in the lineage of Xie et al.
(2019).
}

\subsection{Reproducibility}{

There is no \code{seed} argument (setting the global RNG inside a function is an
R anti-pattern): call \code{set.seed()} before \code{\link[=psave]{psave()}} when stochastic
learners (\code{ranger}, \code{xgboost}) are among the candidates. The resolved
hyperparameters and engine package versions are recorded in
\code{fit$info$learners}.
}
}
